snippet.textDisplay:
For the savory, I'd like to see something that can go really free-form, from basic traditional to really experimental:

Sweet & Sour Chicken

Basically, the lads would need to make 3 components - the rice, bite-sized pieces of fried chicken, and a sauce that's primarily flavored by a combination of some form of sugar and some form of vinegar.

Note: I've mastered around a half-dozen variations of this Chinese staple, including one that's based on watermelon juice. Delightfully light and refreshing, that one.

snippet.textDisplay: I would love to see a Meatloaf recipe-less challenge. It will give the variety of something savory, but it has a lot of possible variations in regards to flavors (seasonings, sauces/glaze etc), options in regards to size (individual portions vs single family style), method of cooking as baked in a tin vs open on a tray, as well as the test of weather it comes out moist or dry (or raw?). And you can include the challenge of what sides to serve with it to complement the flavours of the meatloaf.

I'm watching this with subtitles on, and I noticed a small typo at around 15:25
Ben says "doesn't always go to plan, so a beautiful" and the word he said was actually "segue" not "segway". The two words are pronounced the same way, but a "segway" is a vehicle, and a "segue" is a move from one scene to another.

snippet.textDisplay: challenge, give them a food item they don't know how to cook nor do they have much or any knowledge on it. And all they get is a description of what the taste is like and what it looks like. But no information on ingredients, cooking methods, or similar things. That is a true test for any cook who thinks themself capable. Since it forces you to just make and think about how and what could equal the thing they were told about.
